  "market_context": "Gold on the 60-minute chart is respecting a bearish fair value gap near 1926.7–1927.5, with an old low resting below as external range liquidity. Analyst expects continuation lower from internal to external liquidity.",
  "key_observation": "Price respects the 60-minute fair value gap (internal liquidity) while an unswept hourly low sits below, providing a bearish bias and a clear draw on liquidity for lower-timeframe short entries.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the 60-minute gold chart, identify the bearish fair value gap that price is currently respecting and mark the old low below as the external range liquidity target.",
    "Step 2: Establish bearish bias — price should move from internal range liquidity (the hourly FVG) to external range liquidity (the old hourly low).",
    "Step 3: Drop to the 5-minute chart and wait for the session to open before looking for short setups into that hourly low.",
    "Step 4: On the 5-minute, observe price rallying into a fair value gap; instead of entering directly, wait for confirmation by letting a high form inside the FVG and seeing price respect it with displacement lower.",
    "Step 5: Drop to the 1-minute chart and locate the last up-close candle (order block) where price swept liquidity before displacing down.",
    "Step 6: Enter short at the 1-minute order block with stop above the high inside the 5-minute FVG, targeting the hourly old low."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade resulted in 3.23R profit (per inventory hint).",
  "lessons": "Using internal-to-external liquidity logic on the HTF provides a clean directional narrative; waiting for LTF confirmation (high formed in FVG plus displacement) yields a tight order-block entry with strong risk-to-reward toward HTF liquidity.",
